data.content:
Charles Haughey
An Irish Fianna Fáil politician who served as Taoiseach on three occasions and held various ministerial positions. He was a dominant and controversial figure in Irish politics.<SEP>Charles Haughey was a Taoiseach during the 26th Dáil.<SEP>Charles Haughey was a former Taoiseach and P.J. Mara's political advisor. He was involved in the Arms Crisis.<SEP>Former Taoiseach and key figure in Irish politics, advised by P.J. Mara, involved in the Arms Crisis.

Fianna Fáil
An Irish political party that Charles Haughey led from 1979 to 1992. He served as Taoiseach under this party.<SEP>Fianna Fáil is an Irish political party for which P.J. Mara served as Press Secretary and Director of Elections.<SEP>Irish political party for which P.J. Mara served as Press Secretary and Director of Elections. Also involved in the Arms Crisis.

Taoiseach
The Irish term for Prime Minister. Charles Haughey served as Taoiseach on three occasions.

Dáil Éireann
The lower house of the Oireachtas (Irish Parliament). Charles Haughey served as a Teachta Dála (TD) from 1957 to 1992.

Dublin North-East
A constituency that Charles Haughey represented in Dáil Éireann from 1957 to 1977.

Dublin Artane
A constituency that Charles Haughey represented in Dáil Éireann from 1977 to 1981.

Dublin North-Central
A constituency that Charles Haughey represented in Dáil Éireann from 1981 until his retirement in 1992.

Arms Crisis
An event in 1970 where Charles Haughey was implicated in a plot to import arms for the IRA, nearly destroying his career.<SEP>Political scandal in 1970 involving alleged conspiracy to smuggle arms to the IRA.<SEP>The Arms Crisis was a political scandal in the Republic of Ireland in 1970 involving Charles Haughey and Neil Blaney.

GUBU Affair
A sensational affair in 1982 that damaged Charles Haughey's tenure as Taoiseach.

Castlebar
The town in County Mayo where Charles Haughey was born in 1925.

County Mayo
The county in Ireland where Castlebar, Charles Haughey's birthplace, is located.

County Londonderry
The county in Northern Ireland where Charles Haughey's parents were from.

County Meath
A county in Ireland where Charles Haughey's family moved to after his father left the army.

Donnycarney
A northern suburb of Dublin where Charles Haughey spent his youth.

University College Dublin (UCD)
The university where Charles Haughey studied commerce and became interested in politics.

Trinity College Dublin
A college in Dublin where UCD students, including Haughey, burnt the British Union Jack on VE-day.

King's Inns
An institution where Charles Haughey attended and qualified as a barrister.

Raheny
A place where Charles Haughey lived and from where he was first elected to the Dáil.

Abbeville
A large estate located at Kinsealy, north County Dublin, which became the Haughey family home.

Kinsealy

National Farmers Association (NFA)
An organization that voiced criticism of Charles Haughey's appointment as Minister for Agriculture.

Irish Creamery Milk Suppliers Association (ICMSA)
An organization involved in controversies with Charles Haughey during his time as Minister for Agriculture.

President of Ireland whose re-election campaign Charles Haughey managed in 1966.

Tom O'Higgins
Fine Gael candidate who ran against Éamon de Valera in the 1966 presidential election.

Raidió Teilifís Éireann (RTÉ)
The state-run broadcasting organization that agreed to give Tom O'Higgins a low profile during the 1966 presidential election campaign.

A political rival of Charles Haughey who also ran for leadership of Fianna Fáil.

A political rival of Charles Haughey who also ran for leadership of Fianna Fáil.<SEP>Cabinet minister dismissed for alleged involvement in the Arms Crisis.<SEP>Neil Blaney was a cabinet minister dismissed for alleged involvement in the Arms Crisis.
